# Reference accessed: 2026-05-30 via gh api.
#
# yap is the **on-device speech transcription CLI for
# macOS** by finnvoor — uses Apple's SpeechTranscriber
# framework for offline transcription.  Pivots from
# PHP Symfony Console (R282 peridot) into the **Swift
# language tooling cluster**.  Sister to other Swift
# CLIs (Amethyst window manager, R.swift, swift-lox).
# **MAJOR MILESTONE**: corpus's **first documented
# Swift ArgumentParser CLI** — adds Swift to the
# cross-language CLI taxonomy (22 library variants
# now).
#
# Critical extraction note: yap uses **Swift
# ArgumentParser** library at `import ArgumentParser`
# — corpus's **first documented Swift CLI** AND first
# use of the **ArgumentParser ecosystem**.
# `ArgumentParser` is **the** standard Swift CLI
# library — official Apple-blessed (open source from
# the Swift project itself).  Used by Swift's own
# package manager (swift package), Apple's Vapor
# framework, server-side Swift tools, and macOS CLI
# tooling.  Extends the **cross-language CLI taxonomy**
# to TWENTY-TWO library variants: Rust (6), Go (4),
# Python (3), Crystal OptionParser (R269), Haskell
# optparse-applicative (R270), OCaml Cmdliner (R271),
# C POSIX getopt (R272), Java picocli (R276), Kotlin
# clikt (R277), Scala decline (R278), Dart args
# (R279), Ruby OptionParser (R280), Perl Getopt::Long
# (R281), PHP Symfony Console (R282), **Swift
# ArgumentParser** (R283 — NEW).  **MAJOR PATTERN
# MILESTONE**: 22 cross-language CLI library variants
# documented.  Documents the **Swift property-wrapper
# CLI declaration pattern**:
# ```swift
#   @main struct Yap: AsyncParsableCommand {
#       static let configuration = CommandConfiguration(
#           abstract: "...",
#           subcommands: [Transcribe.self, Listen.self],
#           defaultSubcommand: Transcribe.self
#       )
#   }
#
#   struct Transcribe: AsyncParsableCommand {
#       @Option(name: .shortAndLong, help: "...")
#       var locale: Locale = .current
#
#       @Flag(help: "...") var censor: Bool = false
#
#       @Argument(help: "...") var inputFile: URL
#
#       mutating func run() async throws { /* ... */ }
#   }
# ```
# Distinct from Java picocli's `@Annotation` (R276) —
# both are class/struct-based with annotations on
# fields, but Swift property wrappers are LANGUAGE-
# LEVEL features (not runtime reflection like Java)
# AND ArgumentParser's wrappers generate code at
# compile-time via Swift macros.
#
# Critical extraction note: yap uses **`@main` top-
# level entry point** at Yap.swift:5 — Swift's
# language-level annotation that marks a type as the
# program's entry point.  Combined with
# `AsyncParsableCommand` protocol, ArgumentParser
# auto-generates the main function that parses CLI
# args, dispatches to the appropriate subcommand,
# calls `run()`, and handles errors/exit codes.
# Documents the **Swift @main + protocol-based entry
# point** — distinct from C's `int main()`, Rust's
# `fn main()`, Python's `if __name__ == "__main__"`,
# and Java's `public static void main`.  Swift's
# approach is **DECLARATIVE**: the protocol itself
# IS the entry point spec; the compiler/macro
# generates the actual main fn.  Corpus's **first
# documented `@main` annotation pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: yap uses **5 SUBCOMMANDS
# declared as types** at Yap.swift:9-14 — `subcommands:
# [Transcribe.self, Listen.self, Dictate.self,
# ListenAndDictate.self, MCP_Command.self]` lists
# each subcommand's TYPE (`.self` returns the type
# metadata).  ArgumentParser inspects each type's
# `CommandConfiguration` at compile time to build the
# subcommand tree.  Documents the **subcommand-as-
# type pattern** — distinct from clap derive's enum
# variants (R247+ sncast), Click's nested decorators
# (R266 uvicorn), and decline's typed Command values
# (R278 fs2chat-client).  Swift's approach uses the
# TYPE SYSTEM itself for subcommand registration.
# Plus `defaultSubcommand: Transcribe.self` declares
# the default behavior when no subcommand is given
# — running `yap input.mp3` is equivalent to `yap
# transcribe input.mp3`.
#
# Critical extraction note: yap uses **`commandName:
# "mcp"`** at MCP.swift:9 — overrides the auto-
# derived CLI name (which would be `mcp_command`
# from the Swift type name `MCP_Command` via snake-
# case conversion) to be `mcp` instead.  Documents
# the **explicit CLI-name override** pattern in Swift
# ArgumentParser — useful when the Swift type name
# isn't the desired CLI name (e.g. due to Swift
# naming conventions like underscores or
# CamelCase-with-suffix).  Distinct from Rust clap
# derive's `#[command(name = "...")]` attribute and
# from R249 cairo-profiler's `#[clap(name = "cairo-
# profiler")]` (which served the same purpose).
# Corpus's first documented Swift `commandName`
# override.
#
# Critical extraction note: yap uses **`EnumerableFlag`
# protocol** at OutputFormat.swift:5 — Swift
# ArgumentParser's protocol that turns an enum into
# a **set of mutually-exclusive flag arguments**.
# Each case becomes a SEPARATE FLAG: `--txt` /
# `--srt` / `--vtt` / `--json`.  The variable
# `outputFormat: OutputFormat = .txt` receives
# whichever flag was set.  Documents the
# **EnumerableFlag pattern** in Swift ArgumentParser
# — distinct from:
#   (a) clap derive's `#[derive(ValueEnum)]` (R247+)
#       which makes the enum a VALUE for a single
#       option (e.g. `--format json`)
#   (b) Click's `click.Choice([...])` (R266 uvicorn)
#       — same pattern as clap's ValueEnum
#   (c) Symfony Console's `VALUE_REQUIRED` with
#       suggestions array (R282 peridot)
# Swift's `EnumerableFlag` is **UNIQUE**: it
# transforms an enum into MULTIPLE FLAGS rather than
# multiple VALUES of one flag.  Users write `yap
# transcribe --json input.mp3` instead of `yap
# transcribe --output-format json input.mp3`.
# Documents the **2 enum-style CLI input patterns**:
# (a) enum-as-VALUE (one flag, multiple values), (b)
# enum-as-FLAGS (multiple flags, mutually exclusive).
# Corpus's **first documented enum-as-multiple-flags
# pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: yap uses **`transform:
# Locale.init(identifier:)`** at Transcribe.swift:14
# — ArgumentParser's `transform:` parameter accepts
# a closure (or function reference) that converts
# the raw string CLI input to the target type.
# `Locale.init(identifier:)` is a function reference
# that calls `Locale.init(identifier: rawString)`
# constructor.  Documents the **transform: closure
# pattern** for value conversion — distinct from clap
# derive's `value_parser` (R248 cairo-coverage),
# Click's `type=click.Path(exists=True)` (R266
# uvicorn), and Cmdliner's `Arg.value & file` (R271
# dune).  Swift's approach is the most TERSE — pass
# a function reference, ArgumentParser invokes it
# with the raw string.  Compile-time type-safe.
# Corpus's **first documented Swift transform:
# pattern**.
#
# Critical extraction note: yap uses **`AsyncParsableCommand`
# protocol** instead of `ParsableCommand` at every
# subcommand — enables `async throws` in `run()`
# method.  ArgumentParser's main fn auto-awaits the
# async run method and propagates errors as exit
# codes.  Documents the **AsyncParsableCommand
# protocol** for async/await CLI execution — Swift's
# first-class concurrency support extended to CLI
# tools.  Distinct from Rust's `tokio::main` macro
# (which wraps an async fn) and from Python's manual
# `asyncio.run()` call.  Swift's approach is
# DECLARATIVE: change the conformance from
# `ParsableCommand` to `AsyncParsableCommand` and the
# library handles the async runtime.  Corpus's first
# documented Swift async CLI pattern.

local curcontext="$curcontext" state line ret=1

# 5 subcommands decoded source-direct from Yap.swift
# lines 9-14.
local -a subcommands=(
  'transcribe:transcribe a saved audio/video file (DEFAULT subcommand)'
  'listen:transcribe live system audio in real time'
  'dictate:transcribe live microphone audio'
  'listen-and-dictate:combine listen + dictate modes'
  'mcp:start an MCP server for speech transcription (commandName override; Swift type MCP_Command)'
)

# 4 output format flags via EnumerableFlag protocol
# at OutputFormat.swift.  Each enum case becomes a
# SEPARATE FLAG (not a value of one flag).
local -a output_format_flags=(
  '(--srt --vtt --json)--txt[plain text output (default)]'
  '(--txt --vtt --json)--srt[SRT subtitle format (needs audio time range)]'
  '(--txt --srt --json)--vtt[WebVTT subtitle format (needs audio time range)]'
  '(--txt --srt --vtt)--json[JSON output with timing info (needs audio time range)]'
)

# Common Transcribe args shared with other subcommands.
local -a transcribe_flags=(
  '(-l --locale)'{-l+,--locale=}'[speech locale (BCP-47 identifier; default: current; transform: Locale.init)]:locale:'
  '--censor[replace certain words and phrases with redacted form (@Flag)]'
  $output_format_flags
  '(-o --output-file)'{-o+,--output-file=}'[save transcription output to file (default: stdout)]:file:_files'
  '(-m --max-length)'{-m+,--max-length=}'[max sentence length in chars (default: 40)]:n:'
  '--word-timestamps[include word-level timestamps in JSON output]'
)

_arguments -C \
  '(-h --help)'{-h,--help}'[show help (ArgumentParser auto-adds)]' \
  '(--version)--version[show version]' \
  '1:subcommand:->subcmd' \
  '*::args:->args' && ret=0

case $state in
  subcmd)
    _describe -t subcommands 'yap subcommand' subcommands && ret=0
    ;;
  args)
    case $words[1] in
      transcribe|'')
        _arguments \
          $transcribe_flags \
          '1:input audio/video file:_files' && ret=0
        ;;
      listen|dictate|listen-and-dictate)
        _arguments \
          $transcribe_flags && ret=0
        ;;
      mcp)
        # MCP subcommand has no additional CLI args
        # (acts as an MCP server).
        ret=0
        ;;
    esac
    ;;
esac

return ret
